-- ── Databunker ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Databunker is a free, open-source, self-hosted vault for securely storing and tokenizing sensitive personal records such as PII, PHI, and KYC data, written in Go under the MIT license.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Free / Open Source (with a paid Databunker Pro tier)$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2017, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE($q$Small (open-source maintainer team)$q$, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE(NULL, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Databunker: Open-Source PII & PHI Data Vault Guide$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Databunker is a free, self-hosted, open-source vault for tokenizing and encrypting PII, PHI, and KYC data. See features, MIT licensing, and Pro pricing details.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Databunker is an open-source, self-hosted data privacy vault built in Go, designed to help engineering teams store, tokenize, and protect sensitive personal records such as personally identifiable information (PII), protected health information (PHI), payment card data (PCI), and know-your-customer (KYC) records, without building custom compliance infrastructure from scratch. The project is maintained under the securitybunker organization on GitHub and was created by Yuli Stremovsky, who has written extensively about the motivations behind the project, describing it as a way for developers to isolate and lock down sensitive customer data behind a dedicated, auditable service rather than scattering it across application databases, logs, and backups where it is harder to protect and easier to leak. Databunker is distributed under the permissive, commercially friendly MIT license, meaning organizations can self-host, modify, and even embed it in commercial products without licensing fees, which distinguishes it from many compliance and data-security vendors that require an enterprise sales process. The core architectural idea behind Databunker is tokenization at the record level rather than the field level: instead of replacing individual sensitive values with tokens scattered across a schema, Databunker tokenizes entire user or customer objects, issuing a single UUID token that applications can safely reference, store, and pass around without ever handling the underlying sensitive data directly. Search and lookups against tokenized data are handled through hash-based indexing, which allows applications to query records (for example, by email or phone number) without the vault exposing plaintext values in its indexes. Underlying data at rest is protected with AES-256 encryption meeting FIPS 140-2 standards, and data in transit is protected with TLS. Access to records is governed by a conditional role-based access control model, referred to as CRBAC, which supports field-level masking so that different roles or services can be granted partial visibility into a record without exposing the full data set. Databunker also maintains tamper-evident audit logs that record who accessed which record and when, which is a common requirement for GDPR, HIPAA, and PCI-DSS compliance audits. A notable end-user-facing feature is a passwordless self-service privacy portal, which lets the data subjects whose information is stored in the vault access, correct, or request deletion of their own records, directly supporting data subject access request (DSAR) obligations under regulations like GDPR and CCPA without requiring custom development from the hosting organization. Because Databunker is self-hosted, typically deployed via Docker Compose or a Kubernetes Helm chart, organizations retain full custody of their data and can choose the exact cloud region or on-premises environment where it runs, which avoids introducing an additional third-party data processor into their compliance footprint, an important consideration for regulated industries such as healthcare, fintech, and crypto/Web3 companies handling KYC records. Databunker also supports bring-your-own-key (BYOK) encryption, letting organizations manage their own encryption keys rather than trusting a vendor-held key. Beyond the free open-source core, the project offers Databunker Pro, a commercial edition aimed at enterprise deployments that adds features such as multi-tenancy (allowing a single deployment to isolate data for multiple business units or customers) and more advanced tokenization techniques; pricing for Databunker Pro is not publicly listed and is arranged directly with the vendor. In terms of positioning, Databunker sits in the same general category as commercial data privacy vault products such as Skyflow, Basis Theory, and Very Good Security (VGS), all of which offer similar tokenization-based approaches to isolating sensitive data, but those are typically closed-source, hosted SaaS products with usage-based enterprise pricing, whereas Databunker's core differentiator is that it is free, open-source, and self-hosted, giving smaller companies, startups, and privacy-conscious engineering teams a way to adopt vault-based data protection patterns without a large recurring SaaS bill. It can also be compared loosely to HashiCorp Vault, though HashiCorp Vault is primarily designed for secrets management, such as API keys and credentials, rather than structured customer PII records, making Databunker a more purpose-built solution for customer data privacy use cases specifically. Typical adopters include engineering teams at startups and mid-sized companies that need to demonstrate GDPR, HIPAA, or KYC compliance without hiring a dedicated data-privacy engineering team, as well as companies in regulated verticals such as fintech, healthtech, and cryptocurrency platforms that must securely store identity verification documents and personal data collected during onboarding. Because it is a developer-facing infrastructure tool rather than an end-user application, its primary users are backend engineers, security engineers, and compliance teams responsible for architecting how sensitive data flows through an application stack. As an open-source project, Databunker's roadmap, source code, and issue tracker are publicly visible on GitHub, and the project has published a series of use-case guides covering topics such as PII tokenization, data protection implementation, and BYOK encryption, which double as practical documentation for teams evaluating whether a self-hosted privacy vault fits their compliance and architecture needs. Because the vault runs as a standalone service with its own REST API, it can typically be integrated into an existing application in a matter of days rather than the weeks or months often required to build equivalent tokenization and access-control logic in-house.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = 'd09c518a-e080-4d5d-83f0-8565089486cf';

