-- ── Datadog ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Datadog is a cloud monitoring and security platform that unifies infrastructure metrics, APM, logs, and synthetic testing into one observability dashboard for engineering teams.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Freemium / Usage-based modular pricing$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2010, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE($q$5,000+ employees$q$, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$New York, New York, USA$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Datadog Review 2026: Pricing, Plans & Key Features$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Datadog review 2026: infrastructure monitoring, APM, log management, and security pricing plans, from the free tier to Pro and Enterprise per-host rates explained.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Datadog is a cloud-based observability and security platform that unifies infrastructure monitoring, application performance monitoring (APM), log management, security monitoring, and synthetic testing into a single, modular product suite. The company was founded on June 4, 2010 by Olivier Pomel and Alexis Le-Quoc, two engineers who had previously worked together at Wireless Generation, and it is headquartered in New York City. Datadog went public on the NASDAQ stock exchange in September 2019 under the ticker DDOG and has since grown into one of the largest independent observability vendors, serving tens of thousands of customers across nearly every industry, from technology startups to large financial institutions and media companies. The platform is built around a lightweight software agent that customers install on their servers, containers, or cloud instances, which collects metrics, traces, and logs and streams them to Datadog's cloud backend for aggregation, correlation, and visualization. Because Datadog was designed cloud-native from the start, it integrates deeply with the major public clouds (AWS, Microsoft Azure, and Google Cloud Platform), container orchestration systems like Kubernetes and Docker, and hundreds of common infrastructure and application technologies; the company advertises more than 850 out-of-the-box integrations spanning databases, message queues, web servers, CI/CD systems, and third-party SaaS tools. Datadog's product suite has expanded significantly beyond its original infrastructure-monitoring roots and now includes Application Performance Monitoring (APM) for distributed tracing across microservices, Log Management for centralized log aggregation and search, Real User Monitoring (RUM) and Session Replay for front-end and mobile app performance, Synthetic Monitoring for simulated uptime and transaction testing, Cloud Security Management for detecting misconfigurations and threats, CI Visibility for pipeline performance monitoring, and increasingly, AI-related products such as Bits AI, an AI assistant embedded in the platform, and LLM Observability for monitoring generative AI applications. Pricing at Datadog follows a distinctive modular, product-by-product, usage-based model rather than a single flat subscription: customers are billed separately for each product category they use, typically metered by the number of hosts, containers, users, or the volume of data ingested (for example, gigabytes of logs per month), meaning a customer's total bill scales with both the breadth of Datadog products adopted and the size of their infrastructure footprint. There is a genuinely free tier that supports monitoring for up to five hosts with basic dashboards and a shorter data retention window, useful for individual developers or very small projects to evaluate the platform. Beyond the free tier, Infrastructure Monitoring is offered in a Pro plan, starting at roughly fifteen dollars per host per month when billed annually, which includes access to the 850-plus integrations, prebuilt dashboards, and around fifteen months of metric retention, and an Enterprise plan starting at roughly twenty-three dollars per host per month, which layers on machine-learning-based anomaly detection and alerting along with additional enterprise controls. Other products such as APM, Log Management, and Synthetics are priced and billed independently on their own per-unit metrics (for example, per-million log events indexed, or per-thousand synthetic test runs), which gives customers granular control over cost but also means total Datadog spend can be difficult to predict without careful monitoring of usage; third-party cost-management analyses commonly cite average annual Datadog spend in the tens of thousands of dollars for small and mid-sized businesses and into the hundreds of thousands or more for large enterprises with extensive multi-product deployments. Datadog differentiates itself from competitors through the breadth of its unified platform: rather than requiring separate point solutions for metrics, logs, traces, security, and synthetics, Datadog correlates all of these signals in one interface, which reduces context-switching during incident response and enables cross-signal features like linking a spike in error logs directly to the distributed trace and infrastructure metric that caused it. Its primary competitors include New Relic and Dynatrace, both full-stack observability platforms with broadly similar product breadth; Splunk, which is stronger in log analytics and security use cases but historically weaker in native APM; open-source and self-hosted alternatives such as the Prometheus and Grafana stack, which offer more cost control at the expense of requiring in-house operational effort; and Elastic (the maker of the ELK stack), which competes primarily on the logging and search side. Datadog is most commonly adopted by DevOps, site reliability engineering (SRE), and platform engineering teams responsible for keeping cloud infrastructure and applications healthy, as well as by security teams using its Cloud Security Management products, and increasingly by engineering teams building and operating generative AI features who need visibility into LLM usage, latency, and cost. Notable facts include that Datadog was an early and prominent adopter of the 'shift left' observability trend, encouraging developers rather than only dedicated ops teams to instrument and monitor their own code, and that its mobile applications for iOS and Android let on-call engineers view dashboards and respond to alerts away from a desktop, reflecting the platform's emphasis on incident response speed.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = 'b7e3de09-3d1f-4cf2-8337-c269090981c8';

