-- ── DAViCal ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$DAViCal is a free, open-source CalDAV and CardDAV server for self-hosting shared calendars and address books on a PHP and PostgreSQL stack, licensed under GPLv2.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Free / Open Source$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2007, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE(NULL, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$New Zealand$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$DAViCal: Free Open-Source CalDAV Server Guide$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$DAViCal is a free, self-hosted CalDAV and CardDAV server built on PHP and PostgreSQL. See its features, setup requirements, GPLv2 licensing, and alternatives.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$DAViCal is a free, open-source server application for sharing calendars and address books using the CalDAV and CardDAV protocols, allowing organizations and individuals to self-host their own scheduling and contacts infrastructure rather than relying on a commercial cloud calendar provider. The project was created by Andrew McMillan, a New Zealand-based software developer, and has been maintained largely by him and a community of contributors since its early releases in the mid-to-late 2000s, with widely referenced early version history (such as the 0.9.x release series) dating to around 2007 through 2009. DAViCal is released under the GNU General Public License version 2 (GPLv2), which means it is free to download, use, modify, and redistribute, and its full source code is publicly available, making it a common choice for privacy-conscious individuals, small businesses, educational institutions, and system administrators who want to run their own calendar and contacts server rather than depending on a third-party SaaS provider like Google Calendar or a hosted Exchange server. Technically, DAViCal implements the CalDAV protocol, an open standard, built on top of WebDAV, for storing and synchronizing calendar data (in iCalendar format) between a server and multiple client devices, and it similarly implements CardDAV for contacts and address book synchronization. Although calendar events, tasks, and contacts are transferred between the client and server using the standard iCalendar and vCard formats, DAViCal stores this data internally in a PostgreSQL relational database, requiring PostgreSQL version 8.1 or later as one of its core dependencies, alongside a web server capable of running PHP, since the DAViCal application itself, including its administrative interface, is written in PHP. The project depends on a companion PHP library called Andrew's Web Libraries (AWL), also written and maintained by Andrew McMillan, which provides a range of shared utility functions and objects used throughout DAViCal's codebase. Administration of a DAViCal server, including creating and managing users, calendars, and address books, setting sharing permissions, and configuring principal (user and resource) accounts, is handled through a web-browser-based administrative interface rather than requiring command-line configuration for routine tasks, which lowers the barrier for smaller organizations to operate their own instance. Functionally, DAViCal supports core groupware calendar features that many organizations need: multiple users can read from and write to the same shared calendar over time, calendar owners can delegate read or write access to specific other users or groups, and DAViCal supports free/busy time lookups, which let meeting organizers see when other users on the same server are available before scheduling a meeting, a feature commonly relied upon in corporate calendaring systems. Because it implements an open, standardized protocol rather than a proprietary sync mechanism, DAViCal is compatible with a wide range of third-party CalDAV and CardDAV client applications across desktop and mobile platforms, including calendar apps on Linux, Windows, and macOS, as well as CalDAV-compatible mobile calendar and contacts apps on iOS and Android, and it has historically been paired with companion open-source web clients such as CalDavZAP for browser-based calendar and contact access. DAViCal does not have a commercial pricing structure; it carries no purchase price, subscription fee, or paid tiering, and monetization, where it exists at all in the ecosystem, tends to come from third parties offering paid hosting, installation, or support services around the open-source software rather than from the DAViCal project itself. Because it is self-hosted, the primary 'cost' to an adopter is the effort and expertise required to install, secure, and maintain a PHP and PostgreSQL server stack, along with the ongoing responsibility for applying security updates and backups, which is a materially different cost model from a hosted commercial calendar service. In the landscape of self-hosted calendar and contacts servers, DAViCal is most frequently compared to Radicale, a lightweight Python-based CalDAV/CardDAV server praised for its simplicity; Baikal, a more modern, lightweight CalDAV/CardDAV server also built on PHP; SOGo, a fuller groupware suite that adds webmail and richer collaboration features on top of calendar and contacts sync; and Nextcloud's built-in Calendar and Contacts apps, which layer CalDAV/CardDAV support on top of the broader Nextcloud file-sync and collaboration platform, offering a more modern user interface at the cost of a heavier overall installation. DAViCal's own web-based admin interface and long project history make it a mature, if visually dated, option relative to some of these newer alternatives. Typical DAViCal users are system administrators at small businesses, non-profits, schools, and technical individuals or communities who want full control over their calendar and contact data, need to comply with data-residency or privacy requirements that rule out third-party cloud calendar providers, or simply prefer to avoid dependency on and potential lock-in from commercial calendar platforms. Because it requires manual server setup and is maintained primarily as a community open-source project rather than by a commercial vendor with dedicated support staff, DAViCal is best suited to users with existing Linux server administration experience rather than non-technical end users looking for a plug-and-play hosted calendar solution.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '1107dc4a-e771-4cc9-887a-5ba99556372b';

